---
import AssessmentExperience from '../components/AssessmentExperience.vue';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout>
  <main class="page-shell">
    <section class="hero reveal">
      <div class="hero-copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">Adult autism trait self-check</p>
        <h1>Autism Signals</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          A private self-check for adults who are curious whether their experiences
          overlap with common autistic traits. It is meant for reflection only.
        </p>
        <p class="body-copy">
          If you came here looking for an Asperger&apos;s assessment, this experience uses
          current autism-spectrum language while recognizing that some people still
          identify with the older term. This site is not clinically validated and should
          not be treated as a medical, psychological, or diagnostic tool.
        </p>

        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a class="button-link button-link--primary" href="#assessment">Start the reflection</a>
          <a class="button-link button-link--secondary" href="#guidance">How to read the result</a>
        </div>

        <div class="hero-metrics">
          <article>
            <strong>16 prompts</strong>
            <span>Balanced across communication, sensory profile, flexibility, and history.</span>
          </article>
          <article>
            <strong>4 minutes</strong>
            <span>Short enough to finish, detailed enough to feel grounded.</span>
          </article>
          <article>
            <strong>Private by default</strong>
            <span>Your responses stay in the browser unless you choose to copy them.</span>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>

      <aside class="hero-panel">
        <div class="hero-panel__card hero-panel__card--signal">
          <div class="hero-panel__content">
            <p class="eyebrow eyebrow--soft">What this covers</p>
            <h2>Professional tone, clear boundaries, and useful reflection.</h2>
            <ul>
              <li>Clear prompts about social interpretation, masking, routines, sensory profile, and focus.</li>
              <li>Results that stay careful about uncertainty and never claim to diagnose, validate, or officially screen for autism.</li>
              <li>Optional note-taking so someone can keep track of patterns, questions, and support needs.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="hero-panel__trust">
          <article class="trust-item">
            <img class="trust-item__icon" src="/icons/private-browser.svg" alt="" />
            <div>
              <strong>Private in browser</strong>
              <span>Your responses stay local unless you choose to copy them out.</span>
            </div>
          </article>

          <article class="trust-item">
            <img class="trust-item__icon" src="/icons/informational-only.svg" alt="" />
            <div>
              <strong>Informational only</strong>
              <span>Built for reflection, not validation, diagnosis, or official screening.</span>
            </div>
          </article>

          <article class="trust-item">
            <img class="trust-item__icon" src="/icons/time-gentle.svg" alt="" />
            <div>
              <strong>Takes about 4 minutes</strong>
              <span>Short, calm, and easy to complete in one sitting.</span>
            </div>
          </article>
        </div>
      </aside>
    </section>

    <section class="principles reveal">
      <article class="principle-card">
        <p class="eyebrow eyebrow--soft">Careful by design</p>
        <h2>Not a validated clinical tool</h2>
        <p>
          This experience is intentionally informal. It can help someone notice patterns,
          but it does not produce an official result, medical advice, or a diagnosis.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle-card">
        <p class="eyebrow eyebrow--soft">Adult-aware</p>
        <h2>Built with masking and sensory nuance in mind</h2>
        <p>
          Many adults, especially those who have spent years compensating socially, need
          language that feels more precise than a generic symptom checklist.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle-card">
        <p class="eyebrow eyebrow--soft">Useful output</p>
        <h2>Results that help with self-understanding</h2>
        <p>
          Instead of a blunt pass or fail, the app highlights which themes were strongest
          and helps someone capture language for further reading, reflection, and support.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="experience-section reveal">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow eyebrow--soft">Reflection experience</p>
        <h2>Take the self-check now and get a quick reflection summary in just a few minutes.</h2>
      </div>
      <AssessmentExperience client:load />
    </section>

    <section class="guidance reveal" id="guidance">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow eyebrow--soft">Interpretation guidance</p>
        <h2>What this tool can and cannot tell someone.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="guidance-grid">
        <article class="guidance-card">
          <strong>What a higher result means</strong>
          <p>
            A higher result means more of the prompts felt familiar. It can suggest that
            further exploration is worthwhile, but it does not confirm autism or act as an official screen.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="guidance-card">
          <strong>Why long-standing patterns matter</strong>
          <p>
            Traits that feel lifelong usually matter more in this kind of reflection than
            changes that only appeared recently during stress or burnout.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="guidance-card">
          <strong>Why mixed results still matter</strong>
          <p>
            A mixed result can still be meaningful. Many adults resonate strongly with a
            few domains, such as sensory profile or social fatigue, rather than everything.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="resources reveal">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow eyebrow--soft">Trusted resources</p>
        <h2>Good next reads after the questionnaire.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="resource-grid">
        <a
          class="resource-card"
          href="https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/autism/index.html"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noreferrer"
          data-analytics-event="Clicked Resource"
          data-analytics-resource="CDC overview"
        >
          <strong>CDC overview</strong>
          <span class="resource-card__description">Signs, screening, treatment, and broader background on autism spectrum disorder.</span>
          <span class="resource-card__action">Open resource</span>
        </a>

        <a
          class="resource-card"
          href="https://www.nichd.nih.gov/health/topics/factsheets/autism"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noreferrer"
          data-analytics-event="Clicked Resource"
          data-analytics-resource="NICHD fact sheet"
        >
          <strong>NICHD fact sheet</strong>
          <span class="resource-card__description">Plain-language medical background, including current language around Asperger syndrome.</span>
          <span class="resource-card__action">Open resource</span>
        </a>

        <a
          class="resource-card"
          href="https://www.autism.org.uk/advice-and-guidance/diagnosis/before-diagnosis/signs-that-a-child-or-adult-may-be-autistic"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noreferrer"
          data-analytics-event="Clicked Resource"
          data-analytics-resource="Adult autism signs"
        >
          <strong>Adult autism signs</strong>
          <span class="resource-card__description">A nuanced adult-focused signs page that discusses masking, burnout, sensory profile, and lifelong patterns.</span>
          <span class="resource-card__action">Open resource</span>
        </a>
      </div>

      <p class="support-note">
        If this topic brings up acute distress, use local urgent support or call 988 in the
        United States for immediate mental health crisis help.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="explore reveal">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow eyebrow--soft">Explore more</p>
        <h2>Learn more about the project or share what would make it better.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="support-grid">
        <a class="support-card" href="/about/">
          <strong>About Autism Signals</strong>
          <span>Why this exists, what it is for, and the boundaries it keeps.</span>
        </a>

        <a class="support-card" href="/feedback/">
          <strong>Send feedback</strong>
          <span>Share wording issues, feature ideas, bugs, or anything that would make this more useful.</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <script>
      import { trackEvent } from '../lib/analytics';

      document.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
        if (!(event.target instanceof Element)) {
          return;
        }

        const trackedElement = event.target.closest<HTMLElement>('[data-analytics-event]');

        if (!trackedElement) {
          return;
        }

        const eventName = trackedElement.dataset.analyticsEvent;

        if (!eventName) {
          return;
        }

        const resource = trackedElement.dataset.analyticsResource;
        trackEvent(eventName, resource ? { resource } : undefined);
      });
    </script>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
